{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c944a34d-5b61-43e1-8f6a-8c301ef19b85","content":"In .NET MAUI, `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` moved from `Application` to `Window`. Two main approaches:\n\n**1. Custom Window subclass** (closest equivalent):\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* was OnStart */  }\n    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* was OnSleep */  }\n    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* was OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n```\n\n**2. Inline events** in `App.CreateWindow`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new MainPage());\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Key mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` / `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` / `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `Resumed` |\n\nThere are also additional window events in MAUI (`Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Destroying`, `Backgrounding`) that give you finer-grained lifecycle control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ef1dd987-a382-473c-959b-9c534dda8fd9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle events from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class.\n\nSpecifically:\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event or override `Window.OnCreated`\n\n\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped` \n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated`\n\nThe most straightforward approach is to override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class to return a custom `Window` subclass where you can hook into these lifecycle events, or use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` for platform-specific handling.","outputTokens":836},"id":"30602703-fb0c-4993-b168-a05ce9ac9b99","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:45:36.897Z","parentId":"ac126ee0-ecf8-4fbe-828a-18a9506cf409"}
